## Summary of Input Validation Error Display Patterns

I've found comprehensive validation and error display patterns used in this Easy Salon design system. Here are all the relevant code snippets:

### 1. **Input Component with Label Support** (`src/components/ui/input.tsx`)
The base Input component supports:
- Built-in `label` prop that renders a label above the input with 4px gap
- `required` prop that adds a red asterisk (*) using the `text-destructive` color
- Accepts all standard HTML input attributes

**Key snippet:**
```tsx
interface InputProps extends React.ComponentProps<"input"> {
  label?: string;
}

// Renders as:
<div className="flex flex-col gap-[4px]">
  <Label htmlFor={inputId}>{label}{required && <span className="text-destructive ml-0.5">*</span>}</Label>
  {wrappedElement}
</div>
```

### 2. **FormField Component** (`src/components/forms/FormField.tsx`)
A custom form field wrapper that handles validation errors:

**Error display pattern:**
```tsx
interface FormFieldProps {
  label: string;
  name: string;
  type?: 'text' | 'email' | 'password' | 'tel' | 'textarea';
  value: string;
  onChange: (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement | HTMLTextAreaElement>) => void;
  placeholder?: string;
  required?: boolean;
  error?: string;  // Error message prop
  maxLength?: number;
  mask?: string;
  children?: ReactNode;
}

// Renders error as:
<div className="space-y-2">
  <Label htmlFor={name} className="text-muted-foreground">
    {label} {required && <span className="text-destructive">*</span>}
  </Label>

  <InputComponent
    className={`${error ? 'border-destructive' : ''}`}
  />

  {error && (
    <p className="text-body text-destructive">{error}</p>
  )}
</div>
```

### 3. **shadcn/ui Form System** (`src/components/ui/form.tsx`)
Uses react-hook-form with these components:
- `FormItem`: Container with `space-y-2` class
- `FormLabel`: Label that turns `text-destructive` when there's an error
- `FormControl`: Wrapper using Slot with accessibility attributes (`aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`)
- `FormDescription`: Helper text using `text-sm text-muted-foreground`
- `FormMessage`: Error message display using `text-sm font-medium text-destructive`

**Error message rendering:**
```tsx
const FormMessage = React.forwardRef<
  HTMLParagraphElement,
  React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLParagraphElement>
>(({ className, children, ...props }, ref) => {
  const { error, formMessageId } = useFormField()
  const body = error ? String(error?.message) : children

  if (!body) {
    return null
  }

  return (
    <p
      ref={ref}
      id={formMessageId}
      className={cn("text-sm font-medium text-destructive", className)}
      {...props}
    >
      {body}
    </p>
  )
})
```

### 4. **Real-World Form Validation Example** (`src/components/forms/ServiceForm.tsx`)

**Comprehensive validation pattern:**
```tsx
const [errors, setErrors] = useState<Partial<Record<keyof ServiceData, string>>>({});

const validateForm = (): boolean => {
  const newErrors: Partial<Record<keyof ServiceData, string>> = {};

  // Validation logic
  if (!serviceData.name.trim()) {
    newErrors.name = "Nome é obrigatório";
  } else if (serviceData.name.trim().length < 2) {
    newErrors.name = "Nome deve ter pelo menos 2 caracteres";
  }

  setErrors(newErrors);
  return Object.keys(newErrors).length === 0;
};

// Error display with helper text:
<div className="space-y-1">
  <Input
    id="name"
    label="Nome do Serviço"
    value={serviceData.name}
    className={`salon-input${errors.name ? " border-destructive" : ""}`}
  />
  {errors.name && <p className="text-[13px] text-destructive">{errors.name}</p>}
  <p className="text-[13px] text-muted-foreground">
    Mínimo 2 caracteres, máximo 100 caracteres
  </p>
</div>
```

